{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17597933","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17597933"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:30:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:30:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15432"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15432","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15432"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.24,0.32,0.02,0.24]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8123"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63165"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8123","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8123"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15432"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48616"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7882"},{"type":"tags","id":"8095"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19696"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19699"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20619"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63165","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/63165"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise fit and healthy 36-year-old woman presents to her general practitioner with a four day history of intermittent vomiting and diarrhoea. Her symptoms started after a chicken meal, which she thinks might not have been cooked properly. The vomiting has settled, but the diarrhoea persists. The general practitioner assessed that she most likely has bacterial gastroenteritis and is considering treatment options.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following bacterial pathogens is most likely to warrant antibiotic therapy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Shigella sonnei","Escherichia coli O157:H7","Salmonella enteritidis","Yersinia enterocolitica","Campylobacter jejuni"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECampylobacter jejuni\u003C/strong\u003E infection may warrant antibiotic therapy (usually azithromycin or ciprofloxacin) in severe cases, immunocompromised patients, or when symptoms persist beyond 1 week. Antibiotics can reduce the duration of symptoms and prevent complications.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEscherichia coli O157:H7\u003C/strong\u003E infection should not be treated with antibiotics as this can increase the risk of developing haemolytic uraemic syndrome by promoting toxin release. \u003Cstrong\u003ESalmonella enteritidis\u003C/strong\u003E gastroenteritis is usually self-limiting and antibiotics are not recommended unless the patient is at high risk for invasive disease. \u003Cstrong\u003EYersinia enterocolitica\u003C/strong\u003E infection typically resolves without antibiotics. \u003Cstrong\u003EShigella sonnei\u003C/strong\u003E infection is usually self-limiting in immunocompetent hosts.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EFor most cases of bacterial gastroenteritis, supportive care with fluid replacement is the mainstay of treatment.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Campylobacter infection typically self-resolves but antibiotics may be indicated in severe or prolonged cases","Escherichia coli O157:H7 infection should not be treated with antibiotics as this increases risk of haemolytic uraemic syndrome","Most bacterial gastroenteritis cases are self-limiting and do not require antibiotic therapy"],"references":["Mueller M, Tainter CR. Escherichia coli Infection. [Updated 2023 Jul 13]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK564298/","Sell J, Dolan B. Common Gastrointestinal Infections. Prim Care. 2018 Sep;45(3):519-532. doi: 10.1016/j.pop.2018.05.008. Epub 2018 Jul 9. PMID: 30115338.","Burd EM, Hinrichs BH. Gastrointestinal Infections. Molecular Pathology in Clinical Practice. 2015 May 19:707\u201334. doi: 10.1007/978-3-319-19674-9_50. PMCID: PMC7123654.","Kotloff KL. Bacterial diarrhoea. Curr Opin Pediatr. 2022 Apr 1;34(2):147-155. doi: 10.1097/MOP.0000000000001107. PMID: 35165210.","* \t\tKumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48616"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15432"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48616","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48616"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-20T09:53:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-20T09:54:25+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8123"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"63165"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes"